      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", pp. 72 and 232. But it might fairly be urged that many would see the man besides those who had become Christians. It helps us to understand the passage if we remember with Nösgen (so Bengel) that the expression ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐπὶ τὸν Κ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". applies not to God the Father, but to Jesus Christ, so that we learn that a conversion of the Jewish population at Lydda to the claims of Jesus as the Messiah was the result of the miracle (see also Hackett’s useful note). On the use of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "οἵτινες",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " see Alford’s note on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 7:53",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", quoted by Page (Winer-Schmiedel, p. 235). For the phrase ",
        "children": []
